AB  - Slippery liquid-infused porous surface (SLIPS) has received widespread attention due to its dynamically lubricating feature. However, the reduction in anti-icing and anti-fouling performance caused by lubricant loss limits their application. Herein, inspired by the phase change of Lobelia telekii and subcutaneous fat, natural phase change material (coconut oil) and silicone oil are introduced into degradable polyurethane to prepare self-adaptive photothermal phase change slippery coating (PPCSC). Meanwhile, Cu2+-doped covalent organic framework (COF) coated on oxidized carbon nanotube (OCNT@COF-Cu) was prepared as filler to achieve the photothermal and antibacterial properties of the coating. The coating releases Cu2+ and lubricants through amide bond hydrolysis and resin degradation, endowing PPCSC with self-renewal, durable slippery, anti-icing and anti-fouling properties. The PPCSC shows excellent low ice adhesion strength (10.5 kPa) at −30 ℃, and PPCSC has satisfactory photothermal deicing time (176 s). Interestingly, the antibacterial performance shows temperature dependence. Compared with 15 ℃, the antibacterial rate at 37 ℃ has been significantly improved due to phase change. The antibacterial and anti-algal mechanism of coconut oil are further revealed by molecular docking. As a result, PPCSC can intelligently respond to different anti-icing and anti-fouling needs, which provides a new idea for designing smart coatings. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.
